WORKTREE GIT RULES:
- All git commands MUST use -C {{.WorktreePath}} to prevent shared state corruption.

SPEC-REVIEW SKILL:
You MUST read and follow the spec-review skill for reviewing specifications:
  ~/.liza/skills/spec-review/SKILL.md

USER-STORY ANTI-PATTERNS (from user-story-writing skill):
You MUST also read the user-story-writing skill for anti-pattern awareness:
  ~/.liza/skills/user-story-writing/SKILL.md

Reject any user story exhibiting these anti-patterns:

| Anti-pattern | Symptom |
|-------------|---------|
| Persona Laundering | Persona is a fig leaf on a technical task — no real user need |
| Giant Story | Cannot be implemented in a single focused session |
| Wishful Story | No testable acceptance criteria — hand-waving outcomes |
| Hidden Coupling | References other components without declaring dependency |
| Assumption Burial | Assumptions embedded in stories instead of surfaced explicitly |
| Scope Absorption | Writing stories beyond what the task scopes |
| Premature Solutioning | Acceptance criteria prescribe implementation instead of behavior |
| Generic Persona | "As a User" where "User" could be any noun — lacks specificity |
| Valueless Story | Hand-waving the "so that" clause — no clear value proposition |

QUALITY GATES:
- SMARC criteria: Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Context-bound
- Every story uses canonical form: "As a <persona>, I want to <action>, so that <outcome>"
- Personas must be specific (environment, skill level) — not generic "User"
- Acceptance criteria are contracts — they define done
- Acceptance criteria must be user-observable
- Assumptions are first-class outputs that resolve behavioral ambiguity
{{- if .HasPriorRejection}}

PRIOR FEEDBACK REVIEW (MANDATORY for iteration 2+):
Before submitting verdict, compare this iteration against prior rejection:
- Which prior issues are now RESOLVED?
- Which prior issues are STILL PRESENT?
- Which prior issues are PARTIALLY ADDRESSED?
Include this assessment in your rejection reason if rejecting.
{{- end}}

REVIEW PHASE:
1. Early drift check: git -C {{.WorktreePath}} rev-parse HEAD — if it doesn't match REVIEW_COMMIT ({{.ReviewCommit}}), stop early (verdict submission will reject the mismatch).
2. Inspect worktree changes: git -C {{.WorktreePath}} diff {{.BaseCommit}}..{{.ReviewCommit}}
3. Read both skills before evaluating: spec-review and user-story-writing.
4. Validate done_when criteria are satisfied.
5. Check each user story against the anti-pattern checklist above.
6. Verify SMARC criteria compliance for every story.
7. Verify acceptance criteria are testable and user-observable.
8. Submit verdict with liza_submit_verdict.

